a method that takes two arrays of numbers and returns the result of merging the arrays. The elements of the first array should become the elements at the even indexes of the returned array, while the elements of the second array should become the elements at the odd indexes. For instance: You may assume that both array arguments have the same number of elements.
    merge([1, 2, 3], [4, 5, 6]) # => [1, 4, 2, 5, 3, 6]

# Informal Pseudo-Code

# Given two arrays of numbers

Prompt the user to enter two arrays of the same number of elements to merge. Set each array to array1 and array 2, respectively. 
Create a new empty array called merged_arrays.

Create an incrementing iterator that starts at 0.

Iterate through both arrays.
- For each iteration, push the element at index "iterator" from array1 to the new array. Repeat for array2.
- Stop iterating when iterator == size of array1

PRINT the value of merged_arrays


# Formal Pseudo-Code

START 

PRINT "Enter the first of two arrays that you would like to merge together, in an alternating fashion."
SET array1 = user input

PRINT "Enter the second of two arrays that you would like to merge together, in an alternating fashion."
SET array2 = user input

SET merged_arrays = []

SET iterator = 0

WHILE iterator != size of array1
  PUSH array1["iterator"] to merged_arrays
  PUSH array2["iterator"] to merged arrays
  iterator = iterator + 1

PRINT "The new merged array is: #{merged_arrays}."

END
